title: Allow  multiple key_types in make_credential
body:
CTAP2 allows us to specify a list of acceptable key types during credential creation. This is helpful when supporting devices like Yubikey < 5.2. Normally we'd prefer ED25519, but these older devices don't support it so we want to specify `ED25519` then `ECDSA256` as a fallback.

This change allows `MakeCredentialArgsBuilder::key_type` to be repeatedly invoked to specify multiple key types.

Not sure what the best practice is for testing.

title: Only set uv when explicitly requested
Do not require an resident key to use an user entity
body:
Hi,

I've just come across the fact that the library  is creating an resident key whenever an `PublicKeyCredentialUserEntity` is specified that however the spec also allows for credentials to be created with an `PublicKeyCredentialUserEntity` without them being resident keys. Since specifying an `PublicKeyCredentialUserEntity` is still useful if the authenticator used possesses an display in which case the username can be displayed during an assertion.

Aside from that I'd consider it an bad practice to create an resident implicitly since resident keys pose privacy issues. I therefore propose to separate the creation of an resident key from supplying an `PublicKeyCredentialUserEntity` by renaming `rkparam` to `user_entity` and adding an additional `resident_key` flag.

title: Linux support
body:
This improves Linux support in the repository by removing a lot of the linux specific code and instead relying on the crossplatform nature of `hidapi`. We use the libudev backend which does effectively what we were doing before, but since it happens in the dependency, we don't have to have conditional logic.

This means we can remove the entire fidokey_pi module and not worry about keeping it synchronized with fidopi.

It also means there is just less code to maintain and have to write separate tests for.

title: Remove Rust-Crypto Dependence
body:
The `rust-crypto` library is outdated and has many problems. For me, it's breaking my ability to compile code as it doesn't have a definition for `_rust_crypto_util_fixed_time_eq_asm` on `arm64`/`aarch64`.

I think it would probably be best to move away from using it, but I ran into an issue where `ring` does not support CBC mode. There have been issues opened for this for years so I don't expect it to change anytime soon meaning to move away entirely (and fix the compilation issues), we still need a replacement for AES256 CBC.

To address this I added new dependence on the `aes` and `block-modes` crates. This fully removes `rust-crypto` from the project.

It also passes tests but the tests aren't extensive. @gebogebogebo any good places to start on making sure I haven't broken anything?
